# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: neo4j
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Cypher was largely an invention of Andrés Taylor while working for Neo4j, Inc.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Cypher was originally intended to be used with the graph database Neo4j, but was opened up through the openCypher project in October 2015.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] The language was designed with the power and capability of SQL (standard query language for the relational database model) in mind, but Cypher was based on the components and needs of a database built upon the concepts of graph theory.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] In a graph model, data is structured as nodes (vertices in math and network science) and relationships (edges in math and network science) to focus on how entities in the data are connected and related to one another.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Cypher is based on the Property Graph Model, which organizes data into nodes and edges (called “relationships” in Cypher).
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] In addition to those standard graph elements of nodes and relationships, the property graph model adds labels and properties for describing finer categories and attributes of the data.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] They can hold any number of attributes (key-value pairs) called properties.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Nodes can be tagged with zero or more labels (like tags or categories), representing their different roles in a domain.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Relationships provide directed, named, semantically-relevant connections between two node entities.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] A relationship always has a direction, a start node, an end node, and exactly one relationship type.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Like nodes, relationships can also have properties.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Labels can group similar nodes together by assigning zero or more node labels.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Labels are kind of like tags and allow you to specify certain types of entities to look for or create.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Properties are key-value pairs with a binding of a string key and some value from the Cypher type system.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Cypher queries are assembled with patterns of nodes and relationships with any specified filtering on labels and properties to create, read, update, delete data found in the specified pattern.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] The Cypher's data type system includes many of the common data types used in other programming and query languages.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Supported data types include scalar value types such as boolean, string, number, integer, and floating-point numbers.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] It also supports temporal types like `datetime`, `localdatetime`, date, time, localtime, and duration.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Container data types for maps and lists are available, along with graph types for node, relationship, path, and a void type.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] The Cypher query language depicts patterns of nodes and relationships and filters those patterns based on labels and properties.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Cypher’s syntax is based on ASCII art, which is text-based visual art for computers.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] This makes the language very visual and easy to read because it both visually and structurally represents the data specified in the query.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] For instance, nodes are represented with parentheses around the attributes and information regarding the entity.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Relationships are depicted with an arrow (either directed or undirected) with the relationship type in brackets.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Similar to other query languages, Cypher contains a variety of keywords for specifying patterns, filtering patterns, and returning results.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Among those most common are: MATCH, WHERE, and RETURN.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] These operate slightly differently than the SELECT and WHERE in SQL; however, they have similar purposes.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] MATCH is used before describing the search pattern for finding nodes, relationships, or combinations of nodes and relationships together.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] WHERE in Cypher is used to add additional constraints to patterns and filter out any unwanted patterns.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Cypher’s RETURN formats and organizes how the results should be outputted.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Just as with other query languages, you can return the results with specific properties, lists, ordering, and more.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] The WHERE clause then filters to only keep patterns where the Movie node in the match clause has a year property that is less than the value of the parameter passed in.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] In the return, the query specifies to output the movie nodes that fit the pattern and filtering from the match and where clauses.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Cypher also contains keywords to specify clauses for writing, updating, and deleting data.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] CREATE and DELETE are used to create and delete nodes and relationships.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] SET and REMOVE are used to set values to properties and add/delete labels on nodes.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] MERGE is used to create nodes uniquely without duplicates.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Nodes can only be deleted when they have no other relationships still existing.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] With the openCypher project, an effort began to standardize Cypher as the query language for graph processing.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] As part of this process there have been five face-to-face openCypher Implementers Meetings (oCIMs).
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] The first meeting took place in February 2017 at SAP's headquarters in Walldorf in Germany, coincident with a meeting of the Linked Data Benchmark Council.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] The most recent OCIM took place in Berlin, coincident with the W3C Workshop on Web Standards for Graph Data Management, in March 2019.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] At that meeting, there was a consensus to work towards Cypher becoming a significant input into a wider project for an international standardized Graph Query Language called GQL.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] In September 2019, a proposal for a GQL standard project was approved by a vote of national standards bodies which are members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1 (responsible for information technology standards).
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] As of 2024, the GQL Standard has been published as the standard graph query language under ISO/IEC 39075:2024.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] The first open-source implementation of a subset of the language is already available.
[src:neo4j/cypher-query-language] Aside from the implementation, one can also find a formalization and read the syntax of the specific subset of GQL.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Data modeling is a practice that defines the logic of queries and the structure of the data in storage.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A well-designed model is the key to leveraging the strengths of a graph database as it improves query performance, supports flexible queries, and optimizes storage.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Develop an initial graph data model by extracting entities and decide how they relate to each other.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Test the use cases against the initial data model.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Create the graph with test data using Cypher®.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Test the use cases, including performance against the graph.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Refactor the graph data model due to changes in the key use cases or for performance reasons.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] For a full tutorial, refer to Create a data model.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Marks a node as a member of a named and indexed subset.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A node may be assigned zero or more labels.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A label marks a node as a member of a named and indexed subset.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A node represents an entity or discrete object in your graph data model.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Nodes can be connected by relationships, hold data in properties, and are classified by labels.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A relationship represents a connection between nodes in your graph data model.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Relationships connect a source node to a target node, hold data in properties, and are classified by type.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Properties are key-value pairs that are used for storing data on nodes and relationships.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A Neo4j DBMS that spans multiple servers working together to increase fault tolerance and/or read scalability.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Databases on a cluster may be configured to replicate across servers in the cluster thus achieving read scalability or high availability.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A logical representation of a set of nodes where some pairs are connected by relationships.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] The prescribed property existence and datatypes for nodes and relationships.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Data structure that improves read performance of a database.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Read more about supported categories of indexes.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] Constraints are sets of data modeling rules that ensure the data is consistent and reliable.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] See what constraints are available in Cypher.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A data model defines how information is organized in a database.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] A good data model will make querying and understanding your data easier.
[src:neo4j/data-modeling] In Neo4j, the data models have a graph structure.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Cypher is Neo4j’s declarative and GQL conformant query language.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Available as open source via The openCypher project, Cypher is similar to SQL, but optimized for graphs.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Round brackets are used to represent `(:Nodes)`, and square brackets `-[]→` to represent a relationship between the `(:Nodes)`.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] With this query syntax, you can perform create, read, update, or delete (CRUD) operations on your graph.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] The graph is composed of nodes and relationships, which may also have assigned properties.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] With nodes and relationships, you can build a graph that can express both simple and complex patterns.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Pattern recognition is a key fundamental cognitive process.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] With Cypher, you can use pattern matching, which in turn makes the learning process more intuitive.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Cypher’s constructs are close to natural language and the syntax is designed to visually look like a graph.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] A graph example involving four nodes and three relationships.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] If you want to represent the data in this graph in English, it would read as something like: *"Sally likes Graphs.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] With this query, you turn the information into nodes and relationships, which are the core elements of Cypher.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] The main components in a graph are nodes and relationships.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Nodes are often used to represent nouns or objects in your data model.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] As mentioned previously, nodes are represented as round brackets `(node)` in Cypher.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] The parentheses are a representation of the circles that compose the nodes in the visualization.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Nodes can be grouped together through a label, which works like a tag and allows you to specify certain types of entities in your queries.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Labels help Cypher distinguish between nodes and optimize execution.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] In a relational database context, this would be the same as using SQL to refer to a particular row in a table.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] The same way you can use SQL to query a person’s information from a `Person` table, you can also use the `Person` label for that information in Cypher.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] If part of your query matches nodes that you need to reference in a later part of your query (i.e. in a subclause), you can use **node variables**.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Variables can be single letters or words, and should be written in lower-case.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] For example, if you want to bind all nodes labeled `Person` to the variable `p`, you write `(p:Person)`.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] If you want to use a full word as a variable, `(person:Person)` works exactly the same.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] In a graph database, both nodes and relationships are first-class citizens and they have equal value.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] In a relational database, relationships are only implied via foreign keys and join tables.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] In Cypher, relationships are represented as square brackets with an optional arrow to indicate the direction (e.g.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Graph featuring nodes and relationships.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Relationships **always** have a direction which is indicated by an arrow.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] An undirected relationship does not mean that it doesn’t have a direction, but that it can be traversed in **either** direction.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] While you can’t **create** relationships without a direction, you can **query** them undirected (in the example, using the `MATCH` clause).
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Since Cypher won’t return anything if you write a query with the wrong direction, you can use undirected relationships in queries when you don’t know the direction.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] This way, Cypher will retrieve **all** nodes connected by the specified relationship type, regardless of direction.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Relationship types categorize and add meaning to a relationship, similar to how labels group nodes together.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] It is considered best practice to use verbs or derivatives for the relationship type.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] The type describes how the nodes relate to each other.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] This way, Cypher is almost like natural language, where nodes are the subjects and objects (nouns), and the relationships (verbs) are the predicates that relate them.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Variables can be used for relationships in the same way as for nodes.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Once you specify a variable, you can use it later in the query to reference the relationship.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] This query specifies variables for both the node labels (`p` for `Person` and `t` for `Technology`) and the relationship type (`r` for `:LIKES`).
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] In the return clause, you can then use the variables (i.e.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] `p`, `r`, and `t`) to return the bound entities.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Result for the example query using node and relationship variables.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Properties are used to store additional information and can be added both to nodes and relationships and be of a variety of data types.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] For a full list of values and types, see Cypher manual → Values and types.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Graph example with node and relationship properties.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Properties are enclosed by curly brackets (`{}`), the key is followed by a colon, and the value is enclosed by single or double quotation marks.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] In case you have already added Sally and John as node labels, but want to change them into node properties, you need to refactor your graph.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Refactoring is a strategy in data modeling that you can learn more about in this tutorial.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] Graph pattern matching sits at the very core of Cypher.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] It is the mechanism used to navigate, describe, and extract data from a graph by applying a declarative pattern.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] This bit of Cypher represents a pattern.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] It expresses that a `Person` node with *Sally* as its `name` property has a `LIKES` relationship to the `Technology` node with *Graphs* as its `type` property.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] You can use this pattern in different queries to the database by adding a keyword to make it a **clause**.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] In the same way as nodes and relationships, you can also use variables for patterns.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] For more information, refer to Cypher manual → Patterns → Syntax and Semantics.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] If you want to learn more about writing Cypher queries, you can take the tutorial on how to Get started with Cypher.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] If you are familiar with NoSQL ("Not only SQL") system, you can also learn more on how to make the transition to a graph database.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] With the Cypher Fundamentals course, you can learn Cypher in 60 minutes and practice using a sandbox.
[src:neo4j/getting-started-cypher] For more suggestions on how to expand your knowledge about Cypher, refer to Resources.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] With a property graph database at its core, Neo4j offers an ecosystem of tools, applications, and libraries which aim to help you get started with the technology.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] Learn what a graph database is and how to use it in your projects.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] Learn the principles of a graph database.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] Learn Cypher®, Neo4j’s graph query language, and start thinking about graphs and patterns.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] Discover strategies to model your data and to improve your workflow.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] Read more about the different ways of importing data to your Neo4j graph database.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] Run through detailed examples of how to integrate Neo4j with your preferred programming language.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] Learn how to use Neo4j Graph Data Science, a library of graph algorithms for analysts and data scientists.
[src:neo4j/getting-started] Learn how to export your graph data in Neo4j for display as a visualization.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:neo4j/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:neo4j/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:neo4j/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:neo4j/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:neo4j/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] It is most known for creating the Neo4j Graph database, a graph database management system (GDBMS), which is implemented in Java and accessible from software written in other languages using the Cypher query language through a transactional HTTP endpoint, or through the binary "Bolt" protocol.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] The company contributed to the development of the Graph Query Language (GQL), an ISO-standardized query language for property graphs, and is a founding member of the GraphQL Foundation, an open-source initiative under the Linux Foundation.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Graph database management systems, such as the Neo4j Graph Database, are used in artificial intelligence applications to represent and query relationships within connected data.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] As of 2024, the company was valued at $2.2 billion with over 800 employees and 1,700 customers globally, with deployments across financial institutions, government, retailers, and technology companies.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j has over 300 enterprise customers, including Adobe, Microsoft, Walmart, UBS, and Daimler Truck.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j is developed by Neo4j, Inc., headquartered in San Mateo, California, United States, with locations in Sweden, Germany, the United Kingdom, France, Singapore, and Australia.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] The company was founded in 2007 in Sweden as an open source project by Emil Eifrem, Johan Svensson, and Peter Neubauer, but the idea for the company dates back to a drawing Eifrem sketched on the back of his napkin during a flight in 2000.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j was developed as an alternative to traditional tabular databases for use cases in which data relationships are central to the structure and querying of information.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] It is used in applications such as AI systems, recommendation engines, fraud detection, supply chain, and pharmaceutical research, where traversing relationships between data points is a requirement.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] The name combines "Neo," meaning "new," with "4j," a naming convention in the Java community meaning "for Java." The project was originally called “Project Neo,” and the name Neo4j was adopted when the company was formed.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] The company helped popularize the term “graph database,” thus creating a new market category.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2011, the company relocated to Silicon Valley, while its engineering hub remained in Sweden.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2016, the Neo4j graph database was used in the analysis of the Panama Papers, a data leak that exposed how wealthy individuals and organizations used offshore financial structures to manage and conceal assets.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2017, NASA acknowledged Neo4j’s contribution to Project Orion for its use in retrieving missing data from the Apollo program.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2018, the company launched its Graphs4Good program to support social impact and non-corporate use cases.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Neo4j supported vaccine product development.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j surpassed $200 million in revenue in 2024, and in 2025, it was reported that 84 of the Fortune 100 and over half of the Fortune 500 use Neo4j’s software to build, orchestrate, and deploy graph databases, including in AI systems at Uber, Walmart, and Daimler Truck.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2025, Neo4j announced a $100 million investment in generative AI, including a startup program supporting 1,000 AI-focused companies worldwide; program members include Medium, Shutl (acquired by eBay), and SOUQ (acquired by Amazon).
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2026, the company announced its acquisition of GraphAware, an intelligence analysis software provider for government agencies, as part of its AI investment.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j participates in the AI Alliance and engages with Linux Foundation projects focused on open-source data and AI ecosystems.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j raised $10.6 million in Series A Funding led by Fidelity Growth Partners Europe in 2011.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In November 2012, the company raised $11 million in Series B Funding led by Sunstone Capital.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In January 2015, Neo4j secured $20 million in Series C Funding led by Creandum and Dawn Capital.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In November 2016, Neo4j secured $36 million in Series D Funding led by Greenbridge Partners Ltd.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In November 2018, Neo4j secured $80 million in Series E Funding led by One Peak Partners and Morgan Stanley Expansion Capital, with participation from other investors including Creandum, Eight Roads and Greenbridge Partners.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In June 2021, Neo4j announced $325 million in Series F funding, led by Eurazeo and GV (Alphabet’s venture capital arm), which valued the company at over $2 billion making the company one of the best funded database companies.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In late 2024, the company began preparations for an initial public offering (IPO) on the Nasdaq stock exchange.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] By early 2025, the company announced it had surpassed $200 million in Annual Recurring Revenue (ARR).
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2026, the company continues to maintain its position as the most widely deployed graph database, according to industry rankings, while remaining IPO-ready as market conditions for tech listings stabilize.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j released version 1.0 of its graph database in 2010, version 2.0 in 2013, version 3.0 in 2016, version 3.5 in 2018, aimed at AI and machine learning, and version 4.0 in 2020 with unlimited scaling, partitioning, also known as ‘sharding,’ and role-based access.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2022, version 5.0 of its graph database was released.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j launched Ops Manager, a tool to monitor and manage global deployments in a unified dashboard in 2022, and vector search to its graph database in 2023, expanding contextual search for generative AI and large language models.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In 2025, the company launched agentic AI enterprise offerings; Neo4j Aura Agent lets companies build, test, and deploy AI agents using their enterprise data, providing end-to-end automated orchestration and AIOps for graph-based knowledge retrieval.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j also launched Aura Graph Analytics for cloud data warehouses and data lake platforms, including Oracle, Microsoft SQL and OneLake, Databricks, Snowflake, and Google BigQuery.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In September 2025, Neo4j introduced Infinigraph, a scalable graph database architecture designed for operational, analytical and AI workloads at over 100 terabytes and billions of nodes.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In March 2024, Neo4j and Microsoft announced a collaboration to integrate graph database capabilities into Azure AI services, including Fabric and Azure OpenAI.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] The integration lets users build knowledge graphs, supporting AI use cases such as GraphRAG.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] In June 2024, Neo4j integrated with Snowflake to enable graph analytics and machine learning directly within the Snowflake AI Data Cloud, allowing users access to 65 graph algorithms using SQL.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j has multiple editions for both its self-managed and fully managed offerings.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] As an ACID-compliant transactional database with native graph storage and processing, Neo4j graph database is available in three editions: Community Edition, Enterprise Edition, and Infinigraph Edition.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Community Edition is free and open source software under the GNU General Public License version 3 (GPLv3).
[src:neo4j/neo4j] The Enterprise and Infinigraph Editions are distributed under a closed-source commercial license and includes additional features related to scalability, performance, operability, and security.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] The previous licensing of Enterprise Edition was dual-licensed: GPL v3 (with parts of the code under AGPLv3 with Commons Clause), allowing for clustering, hot backups, and monitoring.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j AuraDB is available in four tiers: Free, Professional, Business Critical, and Virtual Dedicated Cloud.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] The data elements Neo4j stores in its graph database are nodes, edges which connect nodes to one another, and attributes of nodes and edges.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] As of version 2.0, indexing was added to Cypher with the introduction of schemas.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Previously, indexes were supported separately from Cypher.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Database researcher Andy Pavlo from Carnegie Mellon University has questioned graph databases' decision to abandon the longstanding relational model in favor of a custom model.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Researchers from CWI benchmarked a modified version of DuckDB against Neo4j on graph-related workloads and found that, despite being an extension of a relational database running SQL, their implementation outperforms Neo4j in a few specific tasks.
[src:neo4j/neo4j] Neo4j sued PureThink, for utilizing a power created under the terms of the GNU AGPL, to remove a restrictive Commons clause that Neo4j had added to the AGPL license.
